Text.Value: A wise ploy, and it was successful, to an extent. We did not find a cure, but we found our purpose.
Perhaps in time, I can help direct your violence. Until then, I will watch my back.
Are you in control of your actions now?
I'm with you.
I like the deliberate nature of the lie even less than the disorder of your actions.
When I murder her, Bhaal will choose me in her place.
Power always has. But I shall not get too comfortable here.
And they will pose a greater threat than Ketheric.
I go where my enemies are, and they are not here in the shadows. They are in Baldur's Gate.
An old flame?
I fear we could lose everything if we try to take control.
But you had the Prism, did you not? So the Absolute was not the cause.
If there is a way to turn this design toward slaughter rather than control, she will take it.
I am satisfied.
Now I know that those memories are lies.
We'll be heroes - the saviours of Baldur's Gate.
Madness. We need to eradicate the cult and the elder brain.
It was more of an idea than an entity. Pure love. Total power.
Indeed. And now we know that he was not acting alone.
My time will come. With or without you.
There was another with Ketheric - Gortash. Do you know anything about him?
You can stay with me if you swear to follow my lead.
|I've almost a mind to leave now so I need not suffer your buffoonery any further.|
So it's personal? Good - let's take her down.
|You seemed like a powerful ally but I couldn't bring myself to kill the innocent tieflings.|
What would we do with that power?
I expected you would be, but know this...
You are not stupid. When we reach Baldur's Gate and face the other Chosen, you will see that my way is the right one.
Stealing an entire cult is a new one, even for me.
The power of the enslaved elder brain could reshape the world. We could reshape the world.
The Harper may know more - her precious Baldur's Gate was the soil that nourished his growth.
Walking away wouldn't have helped. While the tadpole lives, I can't be free.
Is vengeance the limit of your ambitions?
To impress you.
To watch them suffer - I need no other reason than that.
Completely.
We have a purpose and a bond. By my oath, I will fight with you while that purpose holds.
Most of the time.
Let them think that. There is a short path from saviour to ruler - a short and bloody path. I know it well, and we will walk it together.
Good. Whatever afflicted you, we can leave it in the past, like the corpses in the Grove.
What do you remember of your indoctrination?
No. An omnipresent authority figure controls all of my actions.
My blood ran hot when we broke Ketheric's bones together. But we have greater challenges ahead of us.
It suits you.
There was no god. Orin held me down in a cocoon of flesh, while a mind flayer forced a parasite into my brain. And she laughed at my fear.
A bold gamble. How can you be sure it's possible?
We are bound, then, to travel together, even if we do not yet agree on our ultimate purpose.
Straj.
She is the one who brought me to Moonrise, and into the presence of her so-called god - the Absolute.
I would prefer to put my faith in your strength than the favour of your god. After all, it is Orin and this grand deception that he chose - not you.
First Myrkul, now Bhaal - I feel like we're in over our heads.
|I travel with you now out of necessity not desire or gratitude.|
It's going to be glorious - I can hardly wait.
Good. That is as it should be.
What I propose is nigh on impossible, but if anyone can succeed, it is us. We have the Prism, and we have the courage to slay gods.
|I thought you might be grateful for me keeping you alive|
Only that he serves Bane, which could make him a petty lordling, or a despot capable of bending the world to his will.
Patience. If we do not prepare, Baldur's Gate will be our tomb.
Ketheric was a dead man long before we arrived - a servant of Myrkul, Lord of Bones.
That is all I ask. And remember, I know when your mind is closed.
You killed the dead man. I'm impressed.
|I could have hunted and killed you without your knowing. I hope you do not make a mistake like this again.|
To think I thought her to be speaking for the Absolute. I worshipped that woman.
The cult are a threat to you. That is what matters.
There is no limit to my ambitions. I will enjoy killing Orin, but unlike her, I do not kill for pleasure alone. I kill to gain advantage.
There is violence in your future regardless. With me, you can at least be sure the violence will lead to glory.
And now your path takes you to Baldur's Gate. I shall walk that path with you.
I was just looking for more people to kill.
We must be free if we are to rule - and to be free, we must destroy this cult, and Ketheric's co-conspirators along with it.
I want revenge on those who did this to me.
Coming here was my best chance to learn more about the tadpole. Possibly even cure it.
Stealing an entire cult is a new one, even for me.
I will find her, I will murder her. And I will smile.
The elder brain is the only thing that has ever managed to change my mind. You're welcome to try.
|Why did you choose to incapacitate me yet kill the other leaders? Why free me from my imprisonment and torturers?|
Tempting, but eradicating the brain may be wiser, to put an end to this madness.
That he has enslaved illithids to fulfil his ambitions strongly suggests he is the latter.
That will do. For now. We should speak more of whatever afflicts you, but there will be time for that.
I jest, but it is as good a reason as any. I have done much more foolish things to win the respect of far inferior people.
I'm flattered. Will you be bringing dead rats and birds to my tent now that we share a camp?
It is clear, now, that he was not working alone.
We should not tarry in this charnel house long.
Fine. All I ask of you is that you keep an open mind.
Maybe I'll change your mind.
When I first visited Moonrise, I stood before the Absolute in awe.
In the long history of these Realms, few people have attempted anything so bold.
The future you propose is shaped by violence. I'd prefer to find another way.
There is yet one thing about you that troubles me, though. Something I need you to explain.
A violent urge drives me. I wasn't in control of my actions.
But Baldur's Gate is a mere bauble. We have the chance to seize something much greater. Surely you see it?
You may be right. I'll keep an open mind.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Leaves throne, standing from here on

Text.Value: And for that I am sorry. I will commit all future atrocities for my own gain - and yours, should we stand together.
I would have thought this entire conspiracy of gods and monsters to be impossible if I had not seen it for myself.
That troubles me.
I do not have a home there anymore - my own siblings would slay me.
We make an acceptable team. But there are greater challenges than Ketheric ahead of us.
|I found you intriguing and wanted you as a travelling companion but you seemed too set in your war path|
When we killed the tieflings, at the grove, I was not in control of my actions. You do not have that excuse. So I ask you - why? Why kill them?
I know one of them all too well - Bhaal's blood-letter, Orin.
No - you're staying here in the shadows.
Me too, but I am keen to find joy in the consequences of the killing as well as in the act itself.
If you go to Baldur's Gate, you're going alone.
Drought, famine and warfare are threats to the world as well. Do you intend to eradicate them?
He favours her, and she is one of the founders of this insane cult.
Indeed, she is the one who indoctrinated me with the Absolute's lies.
Good. The world will be safe from your mad ambitions.
But if we are wise, it will be our dominion.
And then we will need no gods. We will be their equal. We will be Absolute.
Without you - without the Prism - I cannot risk going to the city. The Absolute would take my mind again.
We may fail, but we must try.
Nothing worthwhile ever came without loss. But together we have the strength to decide who loses. And to make sure it is not us.
But I will satisfy my war-lust soon, for there are greater challenges than Ketheric ahead of us.
|I'd prefer to not wake up with a knife to my throat because you thought mercy would gain you another "travelling companion|
What can you tell me about Orin?
The cult are a threat to the world. I aim to eradicate them.
She is fierce, vicious, and cruel. In those respects, we are alike - but she is dangerously unpredictable.
Then you are no different than I once was.
I enjoy killing.
So I ask again - why kill the inhabitants of the Grove?
And we have the chance to seize the greatest advantage of all. Surely you see it?
|One more question I have for you|
I will never tire of sitting on dead men's thrones.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: seated on Ketheric's throne in a casual pose, looking very pleased with herself

Text.Value: Jealous? You needn't be -  when Orin is in my hands, her agony will nourish me.
She is the iblith who indoctrinated me with the Absolute's lies.
Once she's dead, the cult will need new leadership - perhaps we can take her place.
I don't care about them, I care about you.
Yes - although I wish we had collaborated on the killing itself.

EditorData.logicalname: wasn't in colony fight against Ketheric

Text.Value: |So you showed mercy to a self-admitted powerful enemy when you had them at their weakest?|
I ask myself the same question, and I don't have an answer.
It is as if you read my mind. Perhaps you did.
True. But do not lose yourself to despair and fatalism. They tried to make victims of us, but we can take this opportunity to become gods.
If the gods stand in our way, we will tear them down. Nothing will deny me my vengeance on Orin.
Why come to Moonrise, where the cult's power is strongest? Why not walk away?
|I'd be more grateful if you had killed me and spared me your intolerable chidlishness.|
|You left your enemy alive so you could have the potential of a travelling companion?|
I was hoping to earn your trust so that I could learn more about the tadpoles.
In killing Ketheric, we fractured the cult's leadership. When we break the other Chosen and claim their Netherstones, we can take control.
I hoped you would - we make a good team.
And I'll never tire of killing their previous occupants. We make a good team.
You committed atrocities in the name of those lies.
Then you misunderstand me.
Madness would be to let the Absolute's potential go to waste.
Does it matter? They were nobody.
During my time in the cult, I came to know one of his co-conspirators all too well - Bhaal's blood-letter, Orin.
We can travel together, but there can be no trust between us.
Now. I am ready to leave this damned place whenever you give the word. The city awaits.
Excellent - I could have used your help against Ketheric. He was a formidable foe.
Shouldn't you be skulking off back to the Underdark?
First we take the Netherstones, then the brain, then the world.
|I prefer to stay alive and it seems you do not. While I'm travelling alongside you, be decisive. Kill our enemies.|
Those who kill without motive cannot be trusted. I would not like to wake with your knife at my throat, and never understand the reason why.
|You carry the wisdom of a child and the foresight of a gambler.|
You make it sound so simple.
You make it sound so simple. She is the Chosen of Bhaal, Lord of Murder, and one of the cult's founders.
Orin was by my side. She told me that god had chosen me to be a True Soul. Blessed and adored.

Synopsis: After the SCE debrief, Minthara sits on Ketheric's throne and dreams of what lies ahead.
